Predicting Diamond Prices¶

Introduction¶

The aim of this assignment is to predict the prices of diamonds using the diamonds data set from the ggplot2 R library.The dataset was sourced from this website https://www.kaggle.com/shivam2503/diamonds.

The report has been divided into the following parts:

  • Overview which contains the information about the dataset and the features involved
  • Data Preparation which involves data cleaning and data preparation order
  • Data Exploration This involves creating the figures and then elaborating on the observations
  • Statistical Modelling and Performance Evaluation This involves creating the full model and exploring figures involving the residual
  • Summary and Conclusion A conclusion of the findings and indications that we observed while exploring this dataset

Overview¶

Data Source¶

The Diamonds dataset provided by the ggplot R library presents 54,940 instances and 10 features. 9 of these features are the explanatory variables and the remaining one is the response variable (price). In this project we use these 9 features provided to predict the price of a diamond.

Project Objective¶

The project objective is to determine the price of a diamond from various features found in the diamond dataset sourced from the ggplot R library. By using various features such as the diamonds carat value and the depth of a diamond we can learn which values correspond with the increment or decerement in price value of an individual diamond.

Target Feature¶

The target feature is Price. This is the price in US dollars (\$326 -- \\$18,823). The feature Price is continuous and numerical. Since our response variable is of these two characteristics our project will be on a regression problem.

Descriptive Feature¶

  • Carat weight of the diamond (0.2--5.01) (units not specified) Continuous
  • Cut quality of the cut (Fair, Good, Very Good, Premium, Ideal) Ordinal
  • Color diamond colour, from J(Worst) to D(Best) Ordinal
  • Clarity a measurement of how clear the diamond is (I1 (worst), SI2, SI1, VS2, VS1, VVS2, VVS1, IF (best)) Ordinal
  • x length in mm (0--10.74) Continuous
  • y width in mm (0--58.9) Continuous
  • z depth in mm (0--31.8) Continuous
  • Depth total depth percentage = z / mean (x,y) = 2 * z / (x + y) (43--79)
  • Table width of top of diamond relative to widest point (43--95) Discrete

Majority of the descriptive features above have intuitive titles which define themselves. The exceptions are descriptive features; x, y and z. Which represent "length", "width" and "depth" respectively. These features all relate to each individual diamonds size.

In [204]:
formula_string_indep_vars = ' + '.join(df.drop(columns='price').columns)
formula_string = 'price ~ ' + formula_string_indep_vars
print('formula_string: ', formula_string)

formula_string:  price ~ carat + cut + color + clarity + depth_total_percentage + table + length_mm + width_mm + depth_mm

formula_string is compatible with Statsmodels module. One issue arrises however, this is that we can't perform automatic variable selection with this formula. Therefore we need to do is 'one-hot-encoding' of categorical features.

In the block of code displayed below we use get_dummies() function in pandas for one-hot-encoding of categorical features. After this we will construct a new string formula with these features.

Too make this more interesting we will add two interaction terms to our full model. We will add the interaction carat with length_mm and table respectively.

In [207]:
formula_string_encoded = formula_string_encoded + ' + length_mm:carat + table:carat'
print('formula_string_encoded: ', formula_string_encoded)

formula_string_encoded:  price ~ carat + depth_total_percentage + table + length_mm + width_mm + depth_mm + cut_Good + cut_Ideal + cut_Premium + cut_Very Good + color_E + color_F + color_G + color_H + color_I + color_J + clarity_IF + clarity_SI1 + clarity_SI2 + clarity_VS1 + clarity_VS2 + clarity_VVS1 + clarity_VVS2 + length_mm:carat + table:carat

We have defined our statistical model formula in a python string. We will now fit an ordinary least squares model to our encoded date.

Note: I had to remove the feature cut_very_good as it was causing issues with sm.formula.ols

Backwards Feature Selection¶

Using p-values we will now perform backwards feature selection

In [252]:
## create the patsy model description from formula
patsy_description = patsy.ModelDesc.from_formula(formula_string_encoded)

# initialize feature-selected fit to full model
linreg_fit = model_full_fitted

# do backwards elimination using p-values
p_val_cutoff = 0.05

## WARNING 1: The code below assumes that the Intercept term is present in the model.
## WARNING 2: It will work only with main effects and two-way interactions, if any.

print('\nPerforming backwards feature selection using p-values:')

while True:

    # uncomment the line below if you would like to see the regression summary
    # in each step:
    ### print(linreg_fit.summary())

    pval_series = linreg_fit.pvalues.drop(labels='Intercept')
    pval_series = pval_series.sort_values(ascending=False)
    term = pval_series.index[0]
    pval = pval_series[0]
    if (pval < p_val_cutoff):
        break
    term_components = term.split(':')
    print(f'\nRemoving term "{term}" with p-value {pval:.4}')
    if (len(term_components) == 1): ## this is a main effect term
        patsy_description.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[0])]))    
    else: ## this is an interaction term
        patsy_description.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[0]), 
                                                        patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[1])]))    
        
    linreg_fit = smf.ols(formula=patsy_description, data=data_encoded).fit()
    
###
## this is the clean fit after backwards elimination
model_reduced_fitted = smf.ols(formula = patsy_description, data = data_encoded).fit()
###
    
#########
print("\n***")
print(model_reduced_fitted.summary())
print("***")
print(f"Regression number of terms: {len(model_reduced_fitted.model.exog_names)}")
print(f"Regression F-distribution p-value: {model_reduced_fitted.f_pvalue:.4f}")
print(f"Regression R-squared: {model_reduced_fitted.rsquared:.4f}")
print(f"Regression Adjusted R-squared: {model_reduced_fitted.rsquared_adj:.4f}")

Summary and Conclusions¶

By utilising the main effects we successfully produced a full model with an adjusted R-squared value of around 92%. Following the backwards variable selection containing a p-value cutoff of 0.05, we removed 3 features while maintaining the same result. In total the final model contained 10 variables (12 including the interaction terms). The final model also had the model p-value equal 0.

The residual scatterplot indicates that no violations of regression assumptions are present. It is safe to conclude that this statistical model is sound and valid. Our adjusted R-squared value is around 92% meaning that the available features are excellent predictors for the price in diamonds. This tells us that these features were perfect fits for predicting price in diamonds.

Although there are a few outliers in the dataset the regression model shows to predict price sufficiently. Out of all the figures produced it is safe to say that the main driving forces of diamond price are size (length, width and depth), clarity and cut. Diamonds of a lower clarity, cut or color tend to need to make up for its price in larger sizes this indicates lower quality diamonds price are more dependent on quantity of diamond, whereas higher quality diamonds make up for their price in craftsmanship of cut, clarity of the diamond and the rarity of color. A simple supply and demand is also present in this dataset whereby higher quality diamonds were less present and rarely reached the sizes of lower quality diamonds therefore they were less abundant, this is another reason as to why we observed higher prices in higher quality diamonds.

Outliers will always be present in datasets and many reasons could inform us as to why we observed outliers in this dataset. Diamonds can increase in price not only due to the features included in this dataset (clarity, size, carat, etc...) but also due to location of the diamond, history of the diamond and ethical sourcing of the diamond. Diamonds that perhaps come from a unique location could very well be another driving factor for price and if the diamonds are not sourced in an ethical manner this can also devalue the diamonds price.

The increase of any value of quality or quantity did not lead to the decline of price in diamonds. A mistake in this data analysis report was the lack of inclusion of colors. I was unable to provide a clear figure explaining the correlation between the price, color and another features interaction. Color in Figure 12 did not exactly show us a direct increase of color rarity with price indicating that color may not be a strong driving force in price. Another feature which lacked emphasis was depth percentage as this did not provide such a meaningful result with price as I had thought.

Overal, it is quite evident that the increase in price of diamonds is very much influenced by the increase of quantity of diamond and quality/rarity of diamonds, the exception was color. What I would fix next time is to perhaps dedicate a whole section comparing color to other features to perhaps find a correlation between color value and price, and find an indication between price and color.
